TextBody:
Hi James,

I have received the below feedback from our R&D team:

Both the Cameron and the Adam logs show that they are running the EPP clients from the 5.9.4 release (version: 6.2.3.1010) and are correctly communicating with the EPP server: "j3p4gni.hosted.endpointprotector.com".

The fact that the EPP Notifier GUI interface is not showing any information and that the EPP server shows many "integrity failure" reports has to do with your certificate trust store configuration.
To fix this situation you will need to ensure that the GlobalSign Certificate Authority is trusted within your environment. Namely, you will need to ensure that the following certificates:

R3 GlobalSign Root Certificate
Valid until: 18 March 2029
Serial #: 04:00:00:00:00:01:21:58:53:08:a2
Thumbprint: d6:9b:56:11:48:f0:1c:77:c5:45:78:c1:09:26:df:5b:85:69:76:ad

and

GlobalSign Code Signing Root R45
Valid until: March 18 2045
Serial #: 76:53:fe:ac:75:46:48:93:f5:e5:d7:4a:48:3a:4e:f8
Thumbprint: 4e:fc:31:46:0c:61:9e:ca:e5:9c:1b:ce:2c:00:80:36:d9:4c:84:b8

Downloadable from this location:  https://support.globalsign.com/ca-certificates/root-certificates/globalsign-root-certificates are trusted on your computers.

To verify this you can navigate to the local path:

"C:Program FilesCoSoSysEndpoint Protector", right click on the "EPPService.exe" file and look at the digital signature. The certificate should be trusted like in the screenshot:






The screenshot also shows the Computer Certificate Manager's trusted certificate authorities list with the GlobalSign code signing root CA selected.  After you update the computer trust store settings you should then reboot the computers.

Please do let us know the outcome after actioning the above.


Kind regards
__________________
